content.thinking:
The `write_meta` function is 12 lines now. I can simplify it by using `serde_json::json!` macro, or I can inline the struct at module level. Let me use `serde_json::json!`:

```rust
fn write_meta(&mut self, meta: &SessionMeta) -> Result<()> {
    let json = serde_json::to_string(&serde_json::json!({
        "type": HEADER_TYPE,
        "version": meta.version,
        "name": &meta.name,
        "created_at": meta.created_at,
        "updated_at": meta.updated_at,
        "provider": &meta.provider,
        "model": &meta.model
    }))?;
    writeln!(self.writer, "{}", json).context("write session header")?;
    Ok(())
}
```

This would be shorter. Or I can use `to_value`:
```rust
fn write_meta(&mut self, meta: &SessionMeta) -> Result<()> {
    let mut value = serde_json::to_value(meta)?;
    if let obj = value.as_object_mut() {
        obj.insert("type".into(), serde_json::json!(HEADER_TYPE));
    }
    let json = serde_json::to_string(&value)?;
    writeln!(self.writer, "{}", json).context("write session header")?;
    Ok(())
}
```

I'm weighing between two approaches: using the `json!` macro for a more direct construction, or converting to a mutable value first and then inserting the type field. The second approach avoids repeating all the fields and feels cleaner.

